*****
[1] Shigellosis, milk - Russia (Yakutia)
Date: Thu 11 Feb 2010
Source: Belarusian News [in Russian, machine trans., edited]
<http://naviny.by/rubrics/disaster/2010/02/11/ic_articles_124_166589/>


According to RIA Novosti, the Office of Rospotrebnadzor [Federal
Service for Consumer Affairs and Human Welfare] in Yakutia has
suspended for 5 days the activity of the Yakutsk dairy factory, due
to production of contaminated milk, which poisoned 155 people,
including 108 children. (According to other media reports, the number
of affected is almost double - BN).

According to the representative of Rospotrebnadzor, 33 individuals
had a bacteriologically confirmed diagnosis of dysentery caused by
_Shigella flexneri_.

"We have conducted a sanitary-epidemiological investigation in the
dairy plant, taken samples of raw materials, finished goods, and
water, and surveyed employees to determine whether they have
bacterial intestinal infections. The audit identified a number of
violations of sanitary legislation for water treatment," said the
agency. The representative of the city of Yakutsk creamery declined
to comment, but the findings of the Rospotrebnadzor audit were confirmed.

--
Communicated by:
HealthMap Alerts via ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[It is unclear if the milk was unpasteurized, poorly pasteurized, or
contaminated after pasteurization. Some cases that are identified may
be secondary family cases as shigellosis spreads quite easily in the
home. Yakutia (also called Sakha) is a large Russian republic in
northeastern Siberia and can be found on a map at
<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sakha_Republic>. The
HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Russia is available at
<http://healthmap.org/r/0178>. - Mod.LL]

******
[2] Cholera - Cambodia
Date: Wed 10 Feb 2010
Source: The Phnom Penh Post [summ., edited]
<http://www.phnompenhpost.com/index.php/2010021031863/National-news/health-experts-at-odds-over-alleged-outbreak-of-cholera-in-provinces.html>


Health experts are at odds over the possibility of a cholera epidemic
breaking out in the Kingdom, with Ministry of Health officials
downplaying the threat and doctors from a Phnom Penh pediatric
hospital saying cases could triple by March 2010 if the government
does not intervene to stop the disease from spreading.

Dr Beat Richner, director of the Kantha Bopha Children's Hospital in
Phnom Penh, said Tuesday [9 Feb 2010] that the disease had been
spreading for months, beginning with 2 confirmed cases in November
2009, followed by 10 in December 2009, 53 in January 2010, and 19 so
far in February 2010 at his hospital alone.

He said his hospital had treated 120 suspected cholera patients in
January 2010, and that all cases had been reported to the Ministry of
Health. But Ly Sovann, deputy director of the Communicable Diseases
Control Department at Ministry of Health, declined to say whether
cholera cases had been confirmed, and argued that the distinction
between diarrhea and cholera was unimportant.

He added that cholera can kill very quickly, and called for a state
of emergency to be declared in areas where a high number of diarrhoea
and suspected cholera cases had been reported, including Kandal, Prey
Veng and Takeo provinces, as well as the capital.

[Byline: Tep Nimol, Brooke Lewis]

