[4] Diarrhea - Fiji (Viti Levu)
Date: Sat 6 Feb 2010
Source: Fiji Times [summ., edited]
<http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=139280>


Dirty water appears to be the main cause of diarrhea cases at the
Colonial War Memorial Hospital, as cases of infected people continue
to rise. Over 200 people have been seen at the hospital in the last
few days, and about 70 percent were admitted.

Ministry of Health spokesman Iliesa Tora said they were trying to
determine the cause of the problem, and this would involve collecting
water samples. He urged members of the public to take their advice
and boil all drinking water.

Mr Tora said no cases have been reported as yet at the Lautoka and
Labasa hospitals. He said parents should carefully monitor their
children, what they eat, and how they live at home.

--
Communicated by:
Seth Edmunds
United States Peace Corps
Kadavu, Fiji
<sethmund@gmail.com>

[ProMED-mail thanks Seth Edmunds for this posting. Colonial War
Memorial Hospital is located in Suva, the capital and largest city of
Fiji. It is located on the southeast coast of the island of Viti
Levu, in the Central Division, Rewa Province, of the Fiji Islands.
Viti Levu can be seen on the maps of the island nation at
<http://www.maps-pacific.com/graphics/Fiji-Islands-Map.gif> and
<http://healthmap.org/r/017b>. - Mod.LL]
